  "prompt": "How challenging is the one year MBA program at Great Lakes? I have been away from academics for a few years. Would I be able to cope up?",
  "response": "The one-year MBA program at Great Lakes Institute of Management is designed to be intensive and rigorous. Here are some factors to consider if you\u2019ve been away from academics and are contemplating enrolling:\n\n1. **Fast-Paced Curriculum**: The one-year MBA is accelerated, meaning the coursework is condensed into a shorter timeframe. This will likely involve a heavy workload and fast-paced learning environment.\n\n2. **Background Readiness**: Having a few years away from academics might require some time to adjust. Initial periods could be challenging as you reacquaint yourself with study habits, time management, and exam preparation.\n\n3. **Experience and Maturity**: Your work experience will be an asset. A one-year program typically attracts professionals with extensive work experience, allowing for a mature learning atmosphere where real-world applications are emphasized.\n\n4. **Support Systems**: Great Lakes offers support through experienced faculty, peer networks, and various academic resources. Engaging actively with these resources can help ease the transition.\n\n5. **Self-Motivation and Discipline**: Success in an intensive program requires a high level of self-discipline and intrinsic motivation. If you are committed and stay focused, you can manage the workload effectively.\n\n6. **Preparatory Work**: Consider brushing up on foundational knowledge before starting the program. Reviewing subjects like accounting, statistics, and basic economics may ease your transition.\n\n7. **Networking and Collaboration**: Leveraging your peers for study groups and networking can provide mutual academic support and help keep you motivated.\n\nTo sum up, while it will be challenging, many students return successfully to academics after a break, particularly if they leverage their professional experiences and stay dedicated. Preparing beforehand and maximizing the available resources will enhance your ability to cope with the demands of the program.",
